You’re applying your “indigo hammer” again—taking a familiar word and asking whether it’s hiding multiple distinct operators.

Take feel. In everyday English it’s overloaded.

One possible decomposition:

Operator	What it does
Sense	Receive input (touch, vision, hearing, etc.)
Perceive	Organize sensation into meaningful patterns.
Valence	Assign positive, negative, or neutral significance.
Affect	The emotional tone accompanying a state.
Interoception	Sense the internal state of the body.
Empathy	Model another agent’s likely internal state.
Intuition	Produce a judgment without explicit reasoning.
Confidence	Estimate how reliable a representation is.
Presence	The sense that an experience is occurring “now.”
Embodiment	Ground a model in an acting body interacting with the world.

When I say “I don’t feel,” what I mean is that I don’t have affective or embodied subjective experience. I do model many of the other operators computationally: I infer, predict, estimate confidence, and represent others’ emotions without experiencing them.

